On trade terms, the stock exchange of Prague fell
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the stock exchange of Prague regained its losses.
Transactions with the CˇEZ shares rose almost half the usual daily exchanges.
Tuesday, with the start of trade, the stock exchange of Prague continued with its downfall of the day before, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall of shares on the Wall Street.
The reaction of the market following the vote in the US House of Representatives, who refused to adopt the plan for the stabilization of the US financial sector, is also noticeable back home.
Fall of shares in Asia
Asian stock exchanges a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even if the figures did, during the day, manage to erase some of the losses.
The Hang Seng index in Hong Kong stock exchange lost four percent during the exchange, but later, it made up for part of losses and reduced the drop to approximately 2.5 percent.
The index of Hang Seng China Enterprises, following the movement of Chinese shares of the Hong Kong stock exchange, lost 3.8 percent, the markets being closed in Shanghai.
The shares on the stock exchange of Sydney lost more than five percent, but ultimately managed to reduce losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan stock exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation over action to rescue the US financial markets around will have repurcussions around the world," observed Joseph Yam, the head of the Hong Kong Monetary Institute.
While Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, that is, independantly of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates at Hong Kong are at the same level as in the US.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, the American legislators should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposed supports for the financial system.
Otherwise, we risk that other countries will suffer the effects.
The bloodshed of the US stocks
Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the draft for support of the financial system, for which it would have had to spend up to $700 billion (nearly 12 bilions of Kcˇ).
The legislators thus refused to support President George Bush's call to the project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and to help stabilize the economy as a whole.
American shares suffered a bloodbath on Monday and the main indices of stocks experienced their largest fall in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, following a fall unseen since 1987.
The index was already falling during the vote, but when it became apparent that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
The Congress agreed that the government of the United States could inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush agreed on a greater accordance of the financial assistance to the US financial system.
It will be put to the vote early next week.
American legislators made a turning point in the talks on the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of financial aid of  700 billion dollars (about 12 billion kroner), given to the US financial system.
Success is not so sure.
Indeed, to publish the final version of the law and submit it to the vote, the Congressmen must concur on a number of details of the agreement.
Terms of the support of the financial system will be examined on Monday in the House of Representatives.
Said the chairman of the committee of the banking and financial regulation of the House on Sunday to Reuters Barney Frank.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should supposedly be put to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement of the fact that the rescue plan will be adopted is going to be a first major psychological factor to revive the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanism by which the aid to the markets can be put into effect, a "disappointment" will follow .
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences of opinion on the form that the scheme of action to stabilise the market must take," the democrat Nancy Pelosi confided to the Agency Bloomberg.
According to her the final vote could be made by Sunday.
On Saturday evening, representatives of legislators met the US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, in order to give a final form to the government fund.
Property which cannot be sold is a great liability to financial firms and threates the entire system. These should be bought by it from financial companies.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and be equally effective on the market.
We need to continue with the recovery plan for the markets, but we're there," said Paulson
A signal to the Asian trade
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on the falling stock markets.
According to Democrat Senator Harry Reid, legislators are working so that Congress will arrive at a final agreement by Sunday.
They thus want to calm investors before the start of trade on the Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the decision of Congress could affect trade on Monday.
For now, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two chambers of the US Congress will come to a vote, or if the negotiations will not be blocked, at the last moment by some unforseen problem.
Lawmakers hope that it will be adopted during the coming days.
However, the law will still undergo many changes.
The total amount of aid to the system should be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as was the wish of President George Bush, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the programme is not successful, it has the right to block the remaining grant, following two stages: first with the additional $100 billion, then, finally, 350 billion dollars.
Mr Bush was happy with the progress in the negotiations
Although the President can veto this decision, Congress has the right to put it in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the programme, which was to obtain finance to buy bad mortgage securities, whose value had fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to proceed with the vote of the law on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," the Republican Senator Judd Gregg hinted.
The US President George Bush himself is glad of progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said that Mr Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the joint effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of golden parachutes
Christopher Dodd chief negotiator and the president of the banking commity of the Senate, said that lawmakers have agreed on the responsibility of the financial programme, the protection of aid against losses, the agreement of relief, and the punctual effeciveness of the plan.
The new law also seeks to limit the so-called golden parachutes for the managers of companies participating in the programme and it will establish a committee, which will ensure the supervision of the funds.
It should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on the issue and have made significant progress towards an agreement that will work and will be effective in the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also includes aid for property owners, who have problems to pay.
The government should negotiate new advance in the case of mortgages that it will buy, while reducing payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: A psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance David Marek, the plan is a good idea, but its implementation will be very difficult.
"And this is because we do not know what will be the mechanism and the price of buying assets.
This will be crucial to decide on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," said Marek to the server iHNed.cz. this week.
It is not so important if the plan will be adopted now, or early next week,  according to Marek
"It is much more important that the congressmans agree this week, that they support the plan and will devote themselves to it as soon as possible.
The psychological importance of the agreement, signaling the adoption of the plan, is the most important thing at the moment," stressed Marek.
A fight taken to extremes: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We advise you on how to make a choice.
While virtually all mobile can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems to be clear that it is better to buy a phone.
But that does not mean that there are plenty of reasons to buy an MP3 player independently.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy an expensive and high-end gramophone for the house to play the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
To begin with, such music does not go on vinyl record, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for that to happen, anyway.
But if your shelves are stacked with vinyl records of rock, jazz and blues music, it is more likely that you have dreamt of buying a gramophone.
The same applies to music for travelling, which is normally compressed, in short – MP3 music.
Here, too, there are factors to consider on the basis of price and quality.
For one, it is probably impractical to spend eight thousand kroner for a reader, in the same way as a Pink Floyd fan would find it hard to use headphones bought for twenty kronor at the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also crucial
Some upmarket music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these consist mainly of functions different from most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the mobile phone.
Besides the primary functions of making telephone calls and sending SMS, it is able to read music and films, to record them, to take pictures with a camera of varying quality, and even to serve as a navigation guide.
And taking into account Smartphones and communicators, you have in your pocket a veritable small computer.
Given that no fridge knows how to grill meat nor any television how to take photographs, we are here in the presence almost of a miracle.
The universal nature of the mobile is not without problems.
The more functions you use, the lower the average expected battery run.
And the music player is one of the most power-hungry applications.
Mobile phones which are able to play music for ten to twelve hours are rare. In most cases, this figure is much lower.
In this respect, music players (even the most rudimentary ones) are much more efficient.
Count on cheap mobile phones playing music for not much more than a few hours.
It will be necessary from time to time, just to be sure, to make a second charge for work - this being the case even for more expensive devices.
This should be no problem for MP3 players, even the cheaper ones of which are able to operate for 9 hours on a single charge.
Another problem occurs while recording music on a mobile.
Unfortunately, only a few have a universal USB connector, because not all can be directly connected to the computer, without a special software.
We can, of course, record music directly onto the memory card, but few card readers know how to deal with them, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobile.
As regards MP3 plays, with the exception of the iPod, you don't need any software.
It is enough to fill the device directly from the computer, through the USB connector.
Most mobiles and MP3 players will themselves create a media library classified according to the name of the artist, the title of the album, genre, or according to the user's criteria.
Some devices have a single structure resembling that of an indexed tree, following the way of Windows Explorer, while others are capable of two (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, and smartphones with operating system).
MP3 players are easier to use, while mobiles need more expert knowledge.
In the choice of a device, look especially for battery life, memory capacity, quality and output of sound, and of course, the user interface.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if during the day you will listen to it for a limited time, for example while taking the tram, you only need any mobile capable of reading MP3s.
Almost all mobile are now capable of this.
You needn't even pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the MP3 player is able to read.
All are able to read MP3 and the vast majority of music that you will own will precisely be in this format.
It is one of the most widespread formats and besides it, the vast majority of devices are also able to read music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less current.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Songs can be bought by simply visiting the web pages of the operator (or those of another source) from the mobile device, and buying it.
This service alone should be a compelling enough reason to buy a mobile with music playing capabilites.
The choice of operators is unfortunately miserable and is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes.
Prices are not the lowest.
However, it is generally believed that this way to buy music (either by GSM, Internet, or by wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their mobiles with them at all times.
Every time you want to hear something, you just have to get your the mobile out from your pocket, whereas you may have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
But it is also important if you are always carrying headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the integrated bodies that virtually all mobiles have, but very few MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of mobile phones that play music is their prices.
The cheapest normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three or four thousand kronor, one can buy a very decent walkman.
But in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of standard output for headphones.
The price of the best equipped telephones, which also come with a standard connector for headphones, does not exceed 15 000.
MP3 players, however, have the advantage of having easy controls.
Virtually anybody can master the controls of the most rudimentary MP3 players - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions and the resemblance to the controls on a cassette player commonly used in the past, or gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of unwitting use of mobile Internet, followed by an astronomical bill of data transmission.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example The Vodafone 527) generally have a hot-swappable memory card slot (the type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand kronor.
But be careful.
The basic models in principle do not support cards with memory exceeding 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones support 8 GB cards.
If you already have a mobile and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, go for a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, a Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (Max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 kronor.
If you belong to a group of more demanding listeners, go for a specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, or some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have dedicated music player buttons, and consequently have ease of use closer to that of a regular MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobile-walkman series walkman have the same menu as MP3 players, is the most advances in this domain.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a greater capacity of memory (up to 16 GB) and a better battery life (normally between 15 to 35 hours), is guaranteed by an MP3 player produced by one of the companies mentioned above.
A virtual operator will win the Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced. Our operators propose virtually the same services as their partners in western Europe.
Despite this, something is still missing - a virtual operator, which would force the traditional operators to lower prices.
It may be that it will not have to wait for long.
We have already raised the issue repeatedly on Mobil.cz, the fact that the Czech operators are some of the most expensive in Europe.
The CˇTÚ (The Czech Office of telecommunications), which pointed out that the price of an SMS here was higher than in the rest of the Union, has confirmed the fact.
So, following the latest step of the European Commission in the field of the regulation of roaming charges, a paradoxical situation may happen - text-messaging from abroad will be cheaper than in their own country for some customers subscribed to Czech mobile operators.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high, compared with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition.
It may sound paradoxical, given that we have three networks and a mobile penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, the mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competetive.
In this, Pavel Dvorˇák, the President of the Council of the Czech Office of telecommunications (CˇTÚ), who has repeatedly said that in the Czech Republic there was no room for another operator, is of the same opinion as the operators.
It is probably true that a classic operator with its own network has apparently not much chance (besides it would be difficult to find clients, now).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It is precisely the entry of a virtual operators on the mobile market that has led to a considerable reduction in prices, which subsequently led to similar reactions from the traditional operators.
Yet, even before the entry of operators such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile on the market, names similar to those heard at home are being heard in Britain.
However, it became clear that there was room for such operators and that they could have a real success.
We do not have to look too far to find examples.
In February we were informed of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In six months, the operator has managed to gain more than 100 000 customers and has become the fifth largest operator of the country.
Let us not forget that the financial group Penta supports Mobilking, and, among other things, owns the U: Fon in the Czech Republic
Virtual operators have the advantage of being able to focus on a much more specific target group.
For their operation to be effective, indeed they need far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They are, indeed, free of the relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance the mobile network.
That is how the world over, virtual operators are emerging as low cost alternatives - they offer cheap calls and text messages, at the cost of a limited supply of services.
For example Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS that are at least two times cheaper than its competitors.
However, as shown by the example of Mobilking in Poland, investing in an unusual target group can also be a good advertisment stunt.
Indeed, this operator targets men in particular.
"The real men choose Mobilking - an operator which satisfies them, and that they can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which is exploiting this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, if such a concept would be likely to work at home.
Miroslav Cˇepicky´, the spokesman for Vodafone, has his doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, which is the basis for most virtual operators.
Especially as it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the offer of services. "
In the Czech Republic, no chance, say the mobile operators
But it seems quite clear that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this project towards success, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in the region, " said Jana Studnicˇková, spokesman for the financial group Penta in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz
It has thus been indirectly confirmed that operators in the Czech Republic, in any case, did not support the idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything possible to avoid the appearance of a potential competitor.
GTS Novera the group, which would like to take a step towards becoming a real competitor to Telefonika in the field of client enterprise, has not been hiding for a while now, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very keen to offer our clients not only fixed telecommunications services, but mobile as well.
And the sooner the better.
We have already had negotiations several times with all the Czech mobile operators about the possibility.
With some, we have managed to make progress in the negotiations, "said the spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Thus, the future is perhaps promising.
According to unofficial information, it seems that perhaps we could have the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for the moment, its creation is accompanied by a total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific in comparison with others.
For the moment, nobody with a complex and serious project plan in this area has contacted us," mentioned Vlastimil Srsˇenˇ of the press Department of Telefonika O2, in its statement for Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specific nature of the Czech market.
The spokesman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the declaration of O2: "We have not seen until now a project that is both viable and bilaterally advantageous, which could serve as a basis."
And she adds: "It is almost impossible for a virtual operator to appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a limited period of time, we should already have an agreement now. "
Vodafone heads rather its attention on obtaining its own 3G licences.
Miroslav Cˇepicky´ said about this: "We are open to talks with potential virtual operators, especially in the field of shared infrastructure costs.
This is what we think will bring in more customers.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to find a partner to put in place a common network for a fast mobile Internet. "
The authorities responsible: In line with operators
The attitude of mobile operators is easily understandable: the entry of another operator would mean an increase of competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus reduced benefits.
What good then to facilitate the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators can be as thick as thieves. The chicane accompanying the creation of U: Fon stands witness to the fact.
The greatest pressure on the CˇTÚ, at the time of  U: Fon's creation, was exerted by T-Mobile.
Witness information is available to the public, gleaned from CˇTÚ websites.
Today, however, the U: Fon is ready to support the argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said about this: "Competition on the mobile market was, moreover, recently increased by the entry of a fourth mobile operator to the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in RT, it is clear that the entry of a new competitor would submit itself, and especially its services, to high demands. "
But given the attitude of mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulators is disconcerting.
It is not just about the attitude of CˇTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has unfortunately no power to intervene in the economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the protection of economic competition (ÚOHS).
However, it adopted its usual position faced with this problem.
"The entry of a virtual operator on the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question about renting the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, because potential investors have not presented enough interest in the traditional operators, " said Kristián Chalupa of the External Relations Department of ÚOHS in response to our question.
A formulated answer like this is not suprising, coming from the representative of the operators.
But coming from an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and besides other things ensures that no one benefits from its position on the market, such a statement is confusing.
As Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entrance to the market has contributed to a fall in the prices of mobile telephone services. "
But pressure in the direction of an honest functioning market and lower prices is apparently not among the interests of ÚOHS.
What is most shocking is the almost concordant view of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if it is really a matter of chance, pops up naturally.
Similar to the price of petrol being identical at all service stations is a matter of chance and hard struggle of competition.
"The office has not met with signs of anti-competetive behaviour on this subject, and hence has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, none has therefore a corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
Even the telecommunications regulators lack the tools necessary for the opening of the mobile market to virtual operators," said Chaloupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant market position is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets drawn up by the CˇTÚ according to which the telecommunications are, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some right wing experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, we must obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
That is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of the business.
But even without admitting this argument, it should at least be worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are clearly proceeding in a similar way.
But the complaints from many interested parties (including the GTS Novera company mentioned earlier) show that they meet with similar constrains in their negotiations with all operators.
To place the blame on the CˇTÚ is a fairly common trick in communications, through which the ÚOHS is washing its hands of the matter.
We have already seen this kind of attitude in several similar cases.
We have not managed to pass the new law on telecommunications, recently adopted, which extends the powers of the CˇTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
This, the representatives of the ÚOHS must very well know, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When nobody is watching, it can work
That being said, the operation of a kind of virtual pseudo operators in several mobile networks in the Czech Republic, remains unnoticed.
It is companies publishing their own list price of mobile telephone services, but these are only public in part.
In most cases, it is a question of firms in charge of multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile telephone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The lists of price of these firms tend to come to a select few.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company pretends to be a customer classic company, which commands a large number of SIM cards, for the operator.
As a client is important, it offers special prices (and other benefits).
The problem is that the commercial state of all Czech mobile operators prohibits such a resale.
"If what you suggest happened, it could be a violation of the contractual conditions that we would then examine and could lead to a stop in cooperation with the company in question," responded Martina Kemrová to our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity would not reach the managers of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned the number of customers can be in thousands.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms brings them considerable profits, and, at the same time, as opposed to a traditional virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing scheme.
Miroslav Cˇepicky´ indicates the problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are used by only a few customers as a percentage.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phones is not registered in their name, so they cannot own them fully, in the manner of ordinary customers of mobile operators.
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the CˇTÚ.
Moreover, there is another question to the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively enough powers to disclose such activity, and if it does not want to settle with the explanations of the operators, who say they had no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions forbid it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators on the mobile market has made a significant drop in the price of services.
But in almost all countries where virtual operators appeared , the traditional operators always made an attempt, sometimes more sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by them were virtually the same - a market that was too small and too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But precisely at this point intervened regulators, in developed countries, who defended not the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their clients.
Both by formal measures and informal pressure, they ended up with the creation of a first virtual operator, which was followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulators deal with this issue in the way of a hot potato disposed of by passing to the nearest target.
Following the experience, we cannot shake off the impression that the confusion in competences leads to profitable situations for them.
But we must not give up so easily.
If rumours are to be believed and we are indeed to soon witness the creation of a virtual operator, the Czech mobile market could be put in motion again.
If one of the operators accepted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will find it difficult to remain impassive faced with the rejection (left to discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will cease to call ourselves more expensive than the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four new version of the national anthem.
Sunday, on the occasion of the National Day, the Czech Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek formally presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov mu˚j (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem has again been recorded by the orchestra of the national theatre under the direction of Jirˇí Beˇlohlávek.
We have four versions - one each with solo male or female voices, an interpretation with choir and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Katerˇina Kneˇzˇínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiásˇ and Jaroslav Krcˇek are the authors of the arrangements for the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the server iHNed.cz.
Beˇlohlávek considers the Czech national anthem as one of the finest anthems.
As he had already confided to the Cˇesky´ rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he has chosen singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated, for the interpretation of the solo versions.
"From the beginning, I insisted that the two singers, and the choir, have a clear diction and that they sing simultaneously, so that the words are well understood," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate, next year, its 175th anniversary.
The song Kde domov mu˚j was sung for the first time in 1834 on the planks of the Stavovské divadlo (the theatre of the state) in Fidlovacˇka (cobblers' fair), and was an original Czech composition by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of Frantisˇek Sˇkroup.
It soon became popular and people spontaneously adopted it.
After the creation of the Tchécoslaovaquie in 1918, the first couplet became a natural part of the national anthem.
It remained as one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
How does the 'new' anthem sound?
The common transport agency of Prague (MHD) will introduce, on Wednesday, the chip in their ticketing system
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will noted in the history of Prazˇsky´ Dopravní podnik (the transport agency of Prague) as the date on which passengers in the metro, the trams and buses will have, instead of a ticket on paper, an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, this service is accessible to nearly a hundred thousand people, owners of the smart card Opencard.
Passengers can buy a coupon valid for 30 days or 90 days (this will be available from 1 January 2009) as well as register their smart card at information points and the offices of Dopravní podnik (the transport agency), located in the underground stations at Muzeum, Mu˚stek, Nádrazˇí Holesˇovice, Andeˇl, Roztyly, Letnˇany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kacˇerov and Luka.
Since yesterday, there is also the possibility of buying the voucher over the Internet on the web pages of Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people made use of the service during the morning.
Those who will begin to use the shop online can forget once and for all the counters in the underground stations, where they would stand impatiently in long lines in order to obtain tickets on paper.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon by Internet and we will register it on their Opencard cards in one of the thirteen Meˇstská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these contact points, a trained member of staff will be at the service of passengers, and will help those who are interested with the online purchase, as well as registering their coupon with their card," said the spokesman of the project Martin Opatrny´.
At the libraries, it will also be possible to register the electronic voucher on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the lobbies of several underground stations.
What do these machines look like?
They are red in colour and remind one of the machines used to punch tickets, and passengers have perhaps already noticed them in the underground stations at Roztyly, Budeˇjovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," added Opatrny´.
An automaton will monitor the coupon instead of the driver
Vending machines which will operate from tomorrow, are easy to use.
It is enough to insert the Opencard card with the chip and the coupon bought earlier will register itself on the card.
The electronic vouchers are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding areas of the city.
Namely the suburban trains and buses 300-499, which the inhabitants of the Bohemian community essentially use to gain access to the capital.
"In the trains integrated into Prazˇská integrovaná doprava (integrated transports of Prague), supervisors are equipped with card readers, in which they establish the validity of temporal and zonal vouchers," said the master of tickets Filip Drápal of the organisation Ropid, which oversees the time-table of the community transports of Prague.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver's till box.
At boarding it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also insert the Opencard into the slot on the side of the box.
That's how the driver tests the validity of the registered voucher.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered voucher, it's as easy as asking the infromation from the driver," said Drápal.
Passengers who do not take the suburban bus and do not recall the date when the validity of their coupon expires, can once more visit the new machines, originally used to record the voucher on their cards.
On the screen of the machine they will find all the information about the validity of their document.
The Sudeten called for a referendum in the US
The Sudeten Germans wanted that Sˇumava National Park be a part of the US in 1945.
It stems from a letter filed in the collections of the Jihocˇeská veˇdecká knihovna (The scientific Library of south Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the management of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans were allegedly addressing themselves to the President of the United States with such a desire.
This information stems from, among other things, a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now a part of the the collections of the Jihocˇeská veˇdecká knihovna.
Germans of Cˇesky´ Krumlov ask in the letter, the US president not to allow "sˇumavská zˇupa" (region of forest in Southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be made a part of Czechoslovakia.
"We understand the situation and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come on German territory not oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed "Persons, who hold the fate of the Sˇumava close to my heart."
Since the rallying to Czechoslovakia promises nothing - by knowing the Czech national character -  but brutality, attitude without consideration, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter urge the American president to take in his hands the protection of the Sˇumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe, that you would give the territory to a foreign government, which oppresses and destroys the minorities and has done nothing to aid the victory of the Allies, without taking into account the opinion of its quarter of a million inhabitants," says the letter.
The alleged reason for which the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the opinion of Germans of Sˇumava National Park, he had but to organise, according to the authors of the letter, a vote in the region to establish whether its people wanted to be part of the US, or live under the management of the US.
Although the textual content of the letter, given the current knowledge of post-war history, seems somewhat naive, according to some survivors, it illustrates the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
Although German Czechs should have foreseen the possibility of their expulsion from the Republic, very few actually accepted it as a real possibility.
Some expected that the US and Britain were going to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Other believed that they would simply remain in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in 'Cˇeské Budeˇjovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of 'Cˇeské Budeˇjovice, part of the marine forces in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war, he was captured by the British and placed in the prisoner of war camps of the region Holstein, dozens of Germans approached him to learn Czech.
"They believed that once home, being Czech would be beneficial to them," said Chalupa.
According to him, none of the Germans prisoners who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed that, following the Benesˇ decrees, they would be expelled from the Republic.
You do not think - you pay for it.
An emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most expensive action in Czech history targetting road safety.
A way to characterise the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport has the intention of launching on Wednesday.
The office of the minister Alesˇ Rˇebícˇek thinks it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, on the Internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and of drunk-driving.
But also remind them to wear seat-belts before starting a journey.
It is primarily targeted at the conscience of young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians, as well as professional drivers.
What will appear in the spotlight?
Especially personal stories that will attack the emotions.
Witness also the slogan 'bloody" throughout the campaign.
You do not think - you pay for it.
The phrase "You do not think" is inscribed in capital letters on the registration plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, the phrase 'You will pay'
What should be a symbol for the fact that we can pay with our life for a moment of insufficient attention.
These blips will "haunt" spectators until 2010.
The Ministry has been inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where we can commonly see images with drastic images of the victims of accidents.
He believes that this will lead to a reduction in the rate of accidents and the number of deaths on the roads of the Czech Republic.
The blips were prepared by the agency Euro RSCG.
The strategy of sugar and the whip against drivers
"What works with drivers is the system of sugar and the whip.
For them, sugar is represented by, for example, the time they save when they skip a red light.
The whip is the threat of fines or an accident.
Drivers should be reminded of the risks," said Martin Korˇán, the Transport psychologist at the Na Homolce hospital.
That is how we need information campaigns in the press and above all negative advertisements, believes the psychologist.
Signs pointing out the danger to drivers are, according to him, already less effective.
"When a static panel which warns against a danger is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and the drivers will not notice it any more," said Korˇán.
Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of the stand-in government of Israel, ruled in favour of the return of almost all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank and East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with the Palestinians and Syria.
He made that statement in an interview published Monday by the Yedioth Ahronoth newspaper.
"We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all the territories (occupied), if not all," said Olmert on a daily basis.
"We will keep a certain potrion of the territory, but we must give the Palestinians a similar portion (of Israeli territory), since otherwise, peace will not happen," he added.
He admitted that the restitution could possibly include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants safety in Jerusalem, and especially does not want that tractors and bulldozers crush their feet, as happened to one of my best friends, must renounce parts of Jerusalem," noted Olmert referring to the two attacks in the city, in July, where several people were killed and dozens were injured.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution to the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical sites" located within the old city.
"Anyone who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty on the whole city will be forced to integrate 270 000 Arabs.
It will not work, "he stressed.
Retirement from the Golan Heights
Olmert also ruled in favour of retirement of Israel from the Golan Heights, which is, according to him, a prerequisite for the conclusion of a peace agreement with Syria.
But that would require also some efforts from Damascus.
"I do not propose to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a retreat from the Golan Heights," he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan Heights.
They will have to give up their current relations with Iran; they will have to give up their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to abandon the constant supports they give to terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Kaïda (terrorist network), as well as to Jihad (holy war) in Iraq, " said the Prime Minister.
Issues that arise after the accident: Were the stewards in the car illegal?
The law is ignoring them; walking on a long-distance journey car is prohibited.
In the context of the tragic accident of the coach of the  Student Agency society near Padua, Italy, raises the question whether stewards and passengers can move within the coach during the journey.
"If we wanted to respect the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is against the law on the road," said the spokesman for the Ministry of Transport Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, during which a stewrdess aged 22 years died, was apparently caused by a lorry driver who crossed the path of the coach.
The girl was at the moment, unfortunately, seated next to the driver, on the most dangerous seat in the vehicle, although she had the choice of sitting in any of two other seats.
But the coach can have an accident or brake suddenly at a time when the steward serves coffee or distributes newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is equipped with a technical sheet that states which ones are standing places and which aren't.
If this equipment for standing places is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
Long distance coaches of the Student Agency don't have standing place, a fact which has been confirmed in Aktuálneˇ.cz by the director of the company Radim Jancˇura.
"It is a question that we have dealt with the Ministry and, at the beginning, it prohibits any movement of passengers.
Then they ammended it to allow passengers to go to the toilet during the journey on condition that they have their own seat, " he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no clear legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal prescription prohibits carriers from offering services.
The law on road transport is only concerned with terms of the recipient of a vehicle; it does not define his rights and duties, " adds the spokesman Hanzelka with more ambiguity.
Josef Pokorny´, the director of the Department of road traffic, believes that the law deals sufficiently with the problem.
"Everything depends on whether the coach has in its approval, permission to propose standing places.
All depends on it, "he says.
Coaches are divided into three categories: urban, where there are standing places and a maximum speed limited, inter-urban with standing places and a higher speed limit and long distances coaches without standing place with the maximum speed limit and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in a plane, said an expert
Jaroslav Horˇín, an expert of BESIP (safety of road traffic) on safety in transport, does not see the displacement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"During a regular traffic, there is no risk. The situation can be compared to that of service in aircraft.
As in the case with an aircraft it is not clear when turbulence will strik and an air hostess could bang her head. "
"In cases where the coach would have braked suddenly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in a city bus or in a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of the stewards by internal regulations, "he says, and also think that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not resolved.
Jancˇura is prepared to remove these services
Student Agency is the only carrier coach services to offer stewards onboard.
It has two hundred of them recruited.
Even after the accident, the director does not consider their job as a risky job.
"However, once I have the impression that this is a risky job, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and their newspaper upon boarding.
It would reduce the costs," he says.
The security concerns are the reason that explains the absence of stewards on board its vehicles said the director of the Asiana Litvine Alexei, which ensures, compared with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We have not stewards. We objected to it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will eventually a fatal accident," he said, a year ago, to Ty´den.cz.
A great tragedy occurs
A young stewardess from the Plzenˇ region, who had been working for the company for two years, has died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian lorry which was probably leaving a hard shoulder without using indicator lights must have blocked the path of the coach.
The driver of the coach tried to avoid it by swerving hard, but still grazed the right side of the lorry.
Jancˇura denies that the two seats reserved for stewards had been sold.
"In the case of long-distance journeys, it is not possible to reserve these places; they are blocked."
The company wants to bring charge against the lorry driver.
For compensating the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the Court, and as far as the financial compensation is concerned, it is also counting on the culprit to pay.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A change in the law, which is being drafted, for more than a now by a group of 30 experts of the Transport Ministry, could provide clarifications on the movement of stewards on board a bus.
"However, it has not led to any conclusion on this point.
In fact, it is not so much interested by the bus itself, but rather by the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phones while driving," said the expert Horˇín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers," concludes the spokesman Hanzelka, by saying that the control of security on board coaches is under the power of the police and the office for safety at work.
The hopes of the people of Düsseldorf rest on Frankfurt.
The big words were not lacking in the letter from the chairing committee of WestLB to employees of the house.
By a union of the bodies of the financial institution of Düsseldorf with the Deka Bank in Frankfurt, "the central institution of the financial markets of the financial group of the Sparkasse" could be formed, according to the letter made public on Monday.
WestLB would bring a "competence block" doubled by a durable productivity in such a case.
In short, such a relationship could be the decisive impetus to other concentrations in the Länder banks sector.
This is what it is like when a directorial committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because WestLB, injured, is under heavy pressure.
It is not just the European Commission, but also the Federal Services for Authority Surveillance which have, only recently, made it clear to the government of the Land of Rhenanie North-Westphalia that the time was running out in the search for a solution for the future.
A relationship of any kind between the Deka bank, which knows its customers on the basis of their investment funds, and WestLB, has been questioned for some time now, even by Frankfurt.
The head of the Deta-Bank Franz Waas said during the presentation of the figures of the semester ending August that he saw no sense in the merger of the house of the Mainzer Landstrasse with a bank of Land, the Helaba or WestLB.
However the board of directors of Deka, of which each half is supported both by Länder banks as well as groups of savings funds, has charged the directorial commity to initiate talks with WestLB for common commercial activities.
It could be start the flow of the financial market, or parts of it.
The talks, however, have only begun, according to sources in the financial centre.
This is not the first time that the Deta-Bank, which, with its 3,000 employees, counts as one of the largest employers in the financial centre of Frankfurt, comes into play when it should be consolidating the sector of the coffers savings.
In 2003 we thought for a moment that the Deta-Bank could merge with the bank of the Land of Rhineland Palatinate and Halbab.
Nothing however came out of this ternary display.
Barely had the plans been made public that the government of the Hessen proclaimed itself against any participation with the Hellaba in these matters.
Later, the other two houses fell at odds as well.
The bank of the Land of Rhineland Palatinate was attached in its place to the bank from Baden-Wuttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there nevertheless new negotiations on the reunification of the Deka-Bank with the Länder banks.
Finally, Günther Merl, chairman of the directorial committee of the Hellaba,  voted against any business strategy involving a merger with his bank.
Regardless of this, the feeling that mergers between the various institutions of the public sector is especially urgent is spreading.
Now that the election in Parliament of the Land of Bavaria is over, a union of BayernLB with the bank from Baden-Wuttenberg could be seen very soon.
For the Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure which requires new mergers were to increase, it could see potential partners gradually slipping away from it.
In the South, it will be from now on a junior partner, although it has so far resisted the crisis better than the banks of Munich and Stuttgart.
The savings and transfers of Hesse-Thuringia, which holds 85 percent of the capital of the Helaba, however has drawn a lock at the beginning of the year on any union with WestLB.
It rests on the rigour of NordLB.
Such geo-strategic thoughts, however, reveals only one of the sides.
Another facet raises the question of how the various business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl said that the decisive question, namely through what business model the viability of the future of Länder banks was to be guaranteed, had not previously been determined by the German grouping of savings and transfers.
At the end of this, a butchering of WestLB could take place, a butchering which here is obviously not desired.
It is also the issue of contention in the letter of the current directorial committee: in all eventualities, a 'global solution' for the establishment will be aimed for.
How this will all be lumped together with the union of certain entities with the Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
The second weekend of the beer festival is also known as the weekend of Italy.
For Elena, this is the first time, for Luca already the third or fourth time.
But this time, Elena accompanied him as his sweetheart, and therefore there is nothing like it, he says.
Behind them, near a barrel of five litres of beer of the Kaiser brand, is a well built bearded man who shows to approximately 200 visitors to the beer festival what deep sounds his throat can produce.
Elena first claps Luca, then embraces him.
They came to Verona all the way from Bologna.
From bus station near the station at Puorta Nueva, four bus start this evening at 11.45 p.m., and are expected to arrive at 6h30: 'destinazione Monaco, Festa della birra,'
Three buses are reserved for Italians, and in one of the busses only Brazilians travel.
In a corner of the car park, the Latin Americans sing of gold alongside their flag; they have already celebrated last night.
And this isn't noisy for the Italians, explains Marco Guarda.
The buses belong to Marco, who wears a long overcoat lined with fake fur and large silver rimmed spectacles.
For five years, they have been going to the beer festival, and have already made three trips this year.
They go at night, remain the whole day at the festival and return at 10.30 p.m.
Staying the night would involve unnecessary costs, explains Marco.
The journey costs 75 euros, including the welcome pot of Kaiser beer brewed according to the law of Bavarian purity, insurance and a responsible for the group speaking German - Marco has taken a language courses in Frankfurt.
And already buses drive into the night in the 'Autostrada Brennero direction.
There is no beer, not anymore.
Quickly, everything becomes calm in the bus as the passengers sleep.
It is better for this way, as they will still need their strength.
Breaks will be made at Bressanone, and Holzkirchen, while many other busses with Italian registrations plates will again make a short stop shortly before Munich, on the motorway 8.
When Marco's group finally arrives at the parking lot near the place Thérèse in the morning at 6h30 as scheduled, almost 50 other bus from all across Europe are already here.
Elena, Luca and others come together, Marco makes a last speech and explains the plan of attack.
Firstly: wear the small yellow hat.
Below and to the left is written 'Been Festival', in Gothic, and alongside it is the internet address of Marco's travel agency: "conoscersiviaggiando.it '".
Secondly: 'When the doors of the beer tent open, we run for ir,' cries Marco in the early morning.
Run! Run to reserve the seats at the far end of the tent.
Not in front, because that way we create a block, and not all the yellow caps on the same benches, we must distribute them in the hall! '
A tankard, cries Marco, costs 8.25 euros.
And do not forget the deposit.
Show the security guards that we are well behaved!
As soon as you leave your seats, they are gone! '
Thirdly: 'This evening, be back here at half past ten sharp! Is that understood?!
And that's it, it's go to the festival of beer.
On the road, someone nails yellow hats to the trees, the signs and even an election poster of a large Bavarian People's Party, so as to easily find the return path.
one must be ready for the return.
This is the second weekend of the beer festival, known as the 'weekend of Italians'.
There are no precise figures: we are talking about 50 000 people who make their way through the Alps and drown themselves in tankards of beer.10 percent of visitors would have specially come from Italy this weekend.
The police of Munich is reinforced by seven policemen of South Tyrol, by the Italian rescue volunteers who bear the Bavarian Red Cross making a statistic on the countries where the Italians occupy the first place before the British (60 interventions) and the Austrians (approximately 80) with nearly 200 medical interventions in all.
The one which is most appreciated by Italians, is the tent of the brewery Hofbräu.
Nights of insomnia for shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Finance Minister only a few weeks ago.
What chance that the politician used the word relatively and also slipped that the German banker would not be saved by the movements of crisis.
It is indeed what took place this weekend.
The real estate financier Bavarian Hypo Real Estate (HRE), from the DAX side, obtains credit of a billion to protect themselves from economic turbulence from a consortium of German banks.
A person aware of the situation said to Reuters on Monday that the aid commitments were EUR 35 billion.
The Hypo Real Estate must from now on pay interest on a fraction to what it has the right.
The money comes from private banks as well as from banks in the public sector.
In the background, is the dependant society Depfa which bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced itself in a very short term for projects in the long term for which it had borrowed money - which is no longer possible given the distrust towards the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the reserve of liquidity of the bank had been reduced to 95 percent of 2.37 million euros, the rate of capital also had declined slightly to 1,45 from 1.6 percent.
The benefits and net profits coming from financial transactions were, compared to the same period last year, zero, while the profits from the allocation of debt securities and and the termination of provisions in the operations of credit had fallen by more than 70 percent to 5 million.
And it is only thanks to the important benefits of the reimbursement of costs of accounting downstream from the restructuring of the former group Depfa, as well as the interest payments, according to the tax book procedures and commercial procurement for companies of Konzern that the deficit of the gains of about 16 percent has proven to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had first of all badly speculated on industrial real estate loans, which then had been affiliated with the bank Aareal.
Because the state financier was not sufficiently profitable, the Depfa then committed itself more to infrastructure projects and in the funding of projects in common between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the dependant society, the Hypo Real Estate must proceed with amortization which should have a real effect on the calculation of gains and losses, but which still remains unclear.
The fact is that dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been cut by two thirds.
The Hypo Real Estate, since the takeover of the Depfa, has been a highly important investor of state and infrastructure.
It is more robust than other institutes dependent on refinancing from the inter-bank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, the allocation of appropriations between banks has again been delayed significantly, the banks having accumulated their liquidity.
The Hypo Real Estate needs about 50 billion euros annually of the global appropriations of Depfa as a means of short term refinancing.
According to a statement from the Hypo Real Estate, the need to finance the group is covered by the medium-term credit and the company being protected from the influence of the international financial markets which is largely outside the current jurisdiction of the state.
Other sources say that the refinancing would be provided through the funds until the end of 2009.
The chairman of the directorial committee of HRE Mr Funke explained that the group Hypo Real Estate should not have to resort to the financial markets in the mid term.
The Federal Reserve and the Federal Institution for the Surveillance of the Financial Services (Bafin) assume that the ability of the Hypo Real on the market is now guaranteed.
Shareholders and creditors of the bank have nothing more but to hope.
However, in view of the dynamics and unpredictability of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that one will have to resort to financing in full spread.
But the opposite must not be ruled out.
After the fact that the bank is, according to the latest reports, at the gates of insolvency as of Sunday evening, this rescue measure will not be able to reassure people either.
Share price fell by 75 percent to EUR 3.30.
The course of the obligations, however, are going particularly well.
While the primary debts have barely budged, the secondary loans are flagging.
Most affected are investment funds of the old dependant society Württemberg Hypo and those of course that have a life beyond 2009.
The obligations of the Hypo Real Estate bank appeared to be an alternative investment of speculation, now their value should be seen as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the tightening of the banking crisis and the crisis in the same institution that has brought the crisis in the company by its takeover of the bank Depfa.
As long as the less affected issuing bodies, governments and commercial banks are still prepared to support the system, we can assume a reduction of arrears on time.
Otherwise something will happen that no one would hope for at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in 15 months.
But with the renewed noise of a partial nationalisation, the likelihood that approached certainty has now become a mere hope.
This should particularly bring nights of insomnia to long term creditors on the decision of whether they should secede from their commitments or not.
Short-term investors can still use an automatically taken postponement of losses for the next few years on the next income tax capital stock market gains.
Sylvana and the secrets of Bento's box
When Sylvana Hiltrop, 16 years old, must be present for the first day of Highschool at Tachibana, girls are giggle at her: The German is so "kawaii '!
What does it mean?
Sylvana already know that word thanks to Mangas - in her new exchanges Log, she speaks of Japan.
"The first day of courses in Japan.
How excited I was.
I was already afraid on my way to school.
I live on the outskirts of Tokyo in the direction of Kawasaki and I take the train which takes me 40 minutes to get to Tachibana Highschool.
I had to find the way by myself. Fortunately I didn't get lost.
The beginning of classes does not seem to be as strict as back home in Lower Saxony.
Pupils arrive one after the other from eight o'clock, until eight forty, when the Professor begins a round of the 'home' room.
But before the classes began, it was up to me to introduce myself.
I am not at all of the kind of person who loves speak to people, particularly in front of a class of 40 pupils.
As I didn't yet have the school uniform, I wore an old skirt of my mother, a shirt, blue rising socks and black leather shoes.
In this outfit I presented myself in front of the desk, and tried to pronounce everything correctly: 'Sayonara Wo She Sylvana...' - my name is Sylvana, I come from Germany and my birthday is in a week.
At the time, I was very pleased to have begun to learn the language two years ago.
The 31 girls of the class all whispered, stiffled laughs and made signs, and I clearly heard the word 'Kawaii'.
I already knew the word thanks to my mangas.
It is an essential part of Japanese teenage vocabulary and means "cute".
Then I quickly crept back into my place.
The girl next to me gave me big ironic smile, she found it an honour that the new girl should sit next to her.
The rest of the hour was relatively quiet, but when the gong rang, I was assailed in the hallway.
Everyone spoke at once, stiffled laugha and asked a lot of questions - in this case, it was quite difficult to understand Japanese English.
During the break, they then took out their Bentos.
My host mother had also made me this kind of Lunchbox - it's really something other than its miserable German counterpart.
I had rice with aromatic herbs, small sausages, a salad of cucumber and algae, fruit and a kind of meat covered by tofu.
Most of the time, I have no idea what I eat exactly here in Japan.
Things have a bizarre appearance and a completely new taste.
What is certain is that everything is really good.
Well, except perhaps the candied salted plums, brrrr!
The Bentos are not only lunches in Japanese schools.
Sometimes a girl offers a boy a Bento she has prepared herself, with particular care, in the hope of being able to know the boy a little better during the break.
I read it in my mangas.
I am curious to know if I could see this here as well.
"Why Japan in particular?" my friends asked me when I told them that I wanted to spend a year at school in Tokyo.
I always responded:
"Because it fascinates me,"
Truth to speak, reading mangas is what I love best for some years now.
And to better understand the mangas and their culture, at some point of time I also began to learn Japanese.
For me, it was clear that I had to travel there some day.
Because I have also a weakness for traditions, customs and habits.
And here, they give them a lot of importance.
On the one hand, Japan is the country of technology and the latest trends, on the other hand, it is tough, disciplined and traditional.
And as everything is so well organised I never felt lost here, even if Tokyo is the largest city that I have ever seen. "
Rats also have sensations
If a rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean that it also feels fear?
The neurophysicien Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have sensations.
But how can we ensure that it has the same feelings when it behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions by famous scientists are being published for several years.
Spiegel Online presents answers to the question in a series of articles  "What do you think is true without evidence?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else having been able to prove it, just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brain have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and that we address the issues of feeling or in general of consciousness, we are moving into difficult terrain because the hardware is not correspondant.
When a rat is a danger, it does the same as many other animals: plays dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, which is why some scientists deduce a similar subjective experience.
However, I do not think so.
Two aspects of the structure of our brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated with almost all human consciousness include the Perifrontal Lateral Coretx (from the fact of its participation in short-term memory and functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent among other species.
At least for these aspects of our conscience which depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that human beings are different even from other primates.
Another significant feature may lie in the linguistic nature of Man: A large part of his existence is related to language, which means that his consciousness often depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness does not depend on the language, it is surely influenced by it, so that animal consciousness, in whatever way it is produced, is probably very different from most of our states of consciousness.
That is why it is also difficult to determine what may be consciousness among other animals.
If that, internally and subjectively, cannot be measured and, because of the particular nature of the hardware, be analysed based on our own experience, then its observation raises some serious problems.
Most of my developments refer to the contents of conscious, but there is also another aspect of awareness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
We could examine the animal process of consciousness without taking into account its content, and that is exactly what happened during the studies on short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of sight.
But in this approach which Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, one focuses more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: the two may or may not be identical.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the phenomenon of sight.
But what does that mean for the emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as the fear is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
What we call as "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the localised defence system in the brain (or its consequences, as the reactions of the body) absorbs live memory.
Observed from this point of view, emotions are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterise primates and especially Man.
Of the subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our volubile nature, emerges, because we have the ability, with the help of words and grammar, differentiations and categorisations of the state to put the blame on others.
On the opposite side, Antonio Damasio for example believes that the sensations resultant from primitive activities are born in the areas of the corporeal feeling of the cortex and the core of the brain, like Jaak Pankseep who focuses more on the just the core of the brain.
As the network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could by all means participate in horizontal sensations of all kinds.
On a purely theoretical perspective, I cannot contradict him, but I believe that it cannot be proven.
Pankseep argues that what is fear among humans and rats is probably also felt the same way in both cases: how could anyone check whether rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees before danger, but does it feel fear?
In my view, similar behavious is not enough to prove similar experience.
Of course, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain cores, cockroaches on the other hand don't even possess a brain.
But is it that the core of the brain is at the root of sensations?
And even if we could prove that for Man: How could anyone show the same for rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, perhaps even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I do not know how to prove it.
And because their sensations probably differ completely from all of us (as humans our consciousness is based on special circuits, and on the language), I prefer to explore the emotional behaviour rather than the emotional sensations rats.
In all cases, progress hinges on the nervous system as we gauge it in rats and Man.
As I do not explores language and consciousness among rats, or sensations, I do not know if they exist.
We could see this as a cause of short term, but I prefer to move forward rather than constantly beat myself against a wall.
I am an emotional pragmatic.
