The fares of plane tickets and hotels is falling
In the first half of 2008, flights and hotels were less expensive than the previous year.
In Germany, according to a current study, flights are cheaper by almost 50 percent.
Flights and hotels will again become profitable - it is the result of a study conducted by a provider of financial services and American Express travels.
The company has analysed reservation data for the first half of 2008 and has established that after a price increase in the first quarter, a sharp fall in profits was witnessed in the second quarter.
After the market prices of hotels have risen for years, bed and breakfasts have already cut their prices in many places.
From January to March, prices rose by 6.9 percent in 41 of 48 examined European cities on average, compared with  the same 41 of 48 examined European cities in 2007.
From April to June, prices were already 3.6 percent lower than in the previous year.
The trend has been marked especially in Paris and Rome, where passengers were paying 30 to 37 percent less than a year earlier.
The causes of this rest for American Express in the weakness of the dollar, which has led to a 'decline in the desire to travel of American tourists'.
Financial markets such as Frankfurt or London would be even more affected by the decline in the price of hotels than industrial cities such as Hanover, Cologne or Stavanger.
In the Swedish town, hotel prices have increased by 26.3 percent, the highest in Europe.
Also in terms of price of flights, the trend was on the rise in the first quarter.
Due to the increase in the price of kerosene, passengers in economy class had to pay an average of 7.1 percent more than in 2007, while on long flights, which consume a lot of fuel, the prices have even gone up by 29.2 percent.
From April to June, the economy class ticket prices have fallen by an average of 12.5 percent compared with the previous quarter, while variation in prices of business-class and first class tickets have been far less pronounced.
In Germany, prices have been falling even more than in other European countries.
From January to March, prices had risen by 11.9 percent in the second quarter, they have fallen by 23.6 percent.
German domestic flights have even been halved according to the study.
The reasons for this fall in prices would be a slowing economic growth, explains the firm.
Demand will acquire ground for many market segments of travel by air.
On the other hand, there is a growing pressure of competition in the "open skies" Treaty liberalising air traffic between the United States and Europe.
Sign of the tense situation is the removal by the airlines of non-profitable routes, and the high number of airlines filing for bankruptcy during the first half of 2008 - there were 24 companies in Europe alone.
