Building societies against the B&B bill.
The British building society may have to pay a bill of more than £80 million to cover the rescue of the Bradford & Bingley bank.
The government has provided £14 billion to protect the deposits of 2.6 million bankers with Bradford & Bingleys.
The interests of the loan will be paid by all companies that collect the dividends from the investors, including 59 building societies.
The Director-General of Building Societies Association (BSA), Adrian Coles said he is "irritated" to know that companies and their members will have to pay the bill...
The loan of £14 billion will be repaid when mortgages of Bradford & Bingleys are released.
But the interests that are at the same time growing, will subsequently be debited, each year, to the 700 financial companies that collect on the deposits.
The Financial Services compensation Scheme confirmed to the BBC, that the 59 building societies are included in the list.
It is annoying to see that the institutions that have had a prudent behavior … must now pay some of the bills of institutions that were much less cautious.
Adrian Coles, BSA
It is being proclaimed that every society must pay a sum proportional to the deposits that it holds, and that intermediate companies must pay about 18% of the cost.
The Treasury estimates that the interests of the loan will rise in 2009, to £450millions.
This means that companies will have to find £81 million to settle the interests of the first year.
Adrian Coles, Director-General of the commercial committee of building societies, told the BBC that this decision was unfair.
It is "irritating" to see that the institutions that have had a prudent behavior during the resumption of the housing market, must now pay for the institutions which were much less cautious.
According to the BSA, no society has failed since 1945, the first date of its history.
"We must examine all aspects of the case for the coming weeks, to assess the options to adopt so as to avoid the building societies and their members paying a hefty bill" said Mr Cole.
The interests of 2009 cover seven months, from the end of September this year till the end of March.
In 2010, it will be necessary to pay the interests of the whole year, which may double.
Given that the building societies are organisations without shareholder, their members end up paying the bill either by higher costs or lower interest rates on savings accounts.
