1001, the antistress number
There are not only 1,000 but 1001 ways to forget the chaos and the frenzy of daily life.
And to top it all, they are all listed in a book which will bring relaxation to bookshops on 30 September.
The alarm makes one sad when it sounds almost every morning at 7 a.m., but it is even worse when one thinks of the agitated rythm that life presents us with.
The office is synonymous with tension and the computer with pain in the back.
Stress is the evil of the twenty-first century.
But there is no one or two methods to combat fatigue daily and the problems linked to the world of work.
But 1001, and not one more or less.
Apart from the positions of yoga, the classic massage or spa treatments, Susannah Marriott gathers in the pages of a book a whole menu of methods suited to the taste and the time of each.
The antistress book is entitled '1001 ways to relax' and will arrive at the booksellers directly from the publisher Pearson Alhambra and DK.
If someone believes that it is not possible to achieve peace in places such as work or through personal relations, this manual demands such a belief.
Moreover, the manual offers other methods such as contact with nature or 100% natural recipes which help to relax.
If adrenalin does not course through your veins to restore the balance of your body and if the stress has become a problem, it is time to sit in the sofa, to disconnect from your spirit and focus on reading.
Speak in sleeping
A few children speak during the night.
I do not refer to those who wake up fully awake and recount something that happened the day before, but children who speak during their sleep.
The first time this happens may surprise you, but in reality it does not matter.
It is a benign change of sleep called somniloquie.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
It is certain that more than one speaks during the night.
This phenomenon can be very sporadic (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with an episode of strong fever), or on a more regular basis (every day, once a week, once a month...); the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause which determines its occurrence
They are often linked to other changes in sleep such as nightmares, terrors of the night, bed-wetting or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have said before, they can also be associated with very high fever, to situations of stress or agitation and excitement.
In any case it is a hardly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it happens is also very different.
It may be that the person speaks with a small, quiet voice, with isolated words, murmurs or on the contrary with cries, tears, long speeches...
In cases where the somniloquie is very frequent, it would be good to observe the child and consult a specialist, to see if there is a problem which causes a lot of anxiety and in order to obtain an explanation for this problem.
We have said that this is a benign alteration, that is why there is no treatment, unless it is linked to a alteration of sleep that can be treated (for example, if it is linked to a sleep disorder or stress).
What we can do is take into account a number of very simple precautions such as:
Try not to excite the child before it goes to sleep.
Therefore find games which are calming and avoid programs or television series that contain violence.
With very nervous children and those who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help calm them internally.
This will allow children to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as somniloquy appears try to stay calm.
Remind yourslef that they are harmless for the child and that the next day it will remember nothing of what happened.
Useful advice
Do not wake the child up.
It is unnecessary since it is unconscious and you are waking it up.
Even if he speaks, he is sleeping and is therefore at rest.
Remind yourself that if the child seems very anxious several times, it is advisable to consult a doctor to check what causes that much anxiety in children.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), don't be tempted to question him to obtain information.
You will achieve nothing, because in sleeping, he is not sufficiently aware to organize his thoughts.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming, because of the way you interpret information and the conclusions you draw from it.
Don't ever tell the child that you can listen to him at night to know his secret.
Not even in joking.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, don't worry, it is nothing bad, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
